The 2nd New Zealand Division began Operation Crusader with {{nowrap|20,000 men,}} of whom {{nowrap|879 were}} killed or died of wounds, {{nowrap|1,699 men}} were wounded, {{nowrap|2,042 were}} taken prisoner ({{nowrap|103 prisoners}} died from all causes), total casualties for the division being {{nowrap|4,620 men.}}{{sfn|Murphy|1961|p=524}} The ''Ariete'' Division had an establishment of {{nowrap|6,231 men}} and had {{nowrap|4,731 personnel}} losses (76 percent) during Operation Crusader.{{sfn|Montanari|1990|pp=738}}{{sfn|TCP|2015|nopp=y}}

===Subsequent operations===

The division reached the XXX Corps lines with little further interruption, where Freyberg concluded that the division must withdraw from the battle and refit, which was agreed to by Norrie. In the early hours the {{nowrap|3,500 men}} and {{nowrap|700 vehicles}} which had escaped, drove east then cut south across the Trigh Capuzzo and retired to the Egyptian border; the 19th Battalion and part of the 20th Battalion joined the Tobruk garrison.{{sfn|Playfair|1960|pp=67–69}}{{sfn|Murphy|1961|pp=458–464}} On the frontier, the 2nd South African Division was ordered to prevent Axis supplies being sent west from Bardia and to mop up Axis positions as soon as an opportunity appeared. The 5th New Zealand Brigade remained under South African command and the rest of the New Zealanders were ordered back to the [[Baggush Box]] to refit.{{sfn|Playfair|1960|p=73}} The retreat from Zaafran left more than {{nowrap|1,000 New}} Zealanders of 18 Battalion, half of 19 Battalion and many gunners in the Tobruk corridor, {{nowrap|3,500 (apart}} from wounded) in Tobruk, more than {{nowrap|3,200 in}} the 5th New Zealand Brigade outside Bardia and hundreds of patients and staff in the New Zealand Medical Dressing Station (MDS) which had been captured.{{sfn|Murphy|1961|p=466}} A lull occurred on 3 December and next day, the cost of the fighting to the Germans was established by German staff officers and a German attack near Ed Duda was repulsed. A report that Bir el Gubi was under attack arrived in the afternoon and Rommel ordered the ''Afrika Korps'' to concentrate against the threat of attacks from the south. Amidst much confusion and indecision from {{nowrap|4–7 December,}} both sides skirmished and during the night Rommel ordered the Axis forces to abandon the besieged forces on the Egyptian frontier and retreat to Gazala.{{sfn|Pitt|1980|pp=143–149}}

